          <h1>Good Hygiene:</h1>
          <p>
            During puberty, the body produces more sweat and oil, which can lead
            to body odor and acne. Good hygiene practices include washing the
            body regularly with soap and water, paying attention to areas that
            tend to sweat more, such as the armpits, groin, and feet. It's
            important to use a mild soap or body wash that is formulated for
            sensitive skin, and to avoid using harsh scrubs or exfoliants that
            can irritate the skin. After washing, it's important to dry the skin
            thoroughly, especially in areas where moisture can accumulate, such
            as between the toes. Using antiperspirants or deodorants can help
            control sweating and odor, and using acne-fighting products, such as
            benzoyl peroxide or salicylic acid, can help prevent or treat acne.
          </p>
