                >Physical Activity for Teenagers</a
              >
              by the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention
            </li>
          </ul>
          <h1 style="margin-top: 2rem">Sleep</h1>
          <p>
            During puberty, the body requires more sleep than adults, with most
            teenagers needing between 8-10 hours of sleep per night. Getting
            enough sleep is important for physical and mental health, as it
            supports growth and development, improves cognitive function, and
            helps regulate mood. To improve sleep quality, teenagers should
            establish a regular sleep routine by going to bed and waking up at
            the same time each day, even on weekends. It's also important to
            avoid screen time before bed, as the blue light emitted from
            electronic devices can disrupt sleep. Creating a sleep-friendly
            environment that is quiet, cool, and dark can also promote better
            sleep quality.
          </p>
          <h3>Resources for Sleep</h3>
